The audit-trail service.

The audit-trail service records every ay-pee-eye call made in your account, console clicks, command-line invocations, software-development-kit calls, and service-to-service calls, and every event captures the same five fields: who, the principal that made it; what, the action; when, the timestamp; where, the source address, agent, and region; and the result, success or an error code with the request parameters. It's the audit trail for everything that happens, and the answer to who-did-that questions.

There are three event types. Management events are control-plane operations, creating, modifying, and deleting resources; they're on by default and free, retained as a queryable ninety-day history in the console with no setup. Data events are data-plane operations, like reading an object or invoking a function; they're opt-in and charged. And insights events are machine-flagged anomalies in call volumes, also opt-in.

For longer retention or for data and insights events, you create a trail that delivers events to object storage, and two settings matter: a multi-region trail captures events from every region into one bucket, the recommended default, and an organization trail captures events from every account into a central bucket, the standard pattern for audit teams. The insights feature baselines normal call volumes and emits an event on a sudden spike or cessation, like an account deleting two hundred security groups in five minutes when it normally deletes none. And enabling log-file validation publishes hourly cryptographic digests so you can detect tampering, which paired with object lock on the bucket gives you a tamper-resistant audit trail.
